<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-948-538  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 948 538.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Nov 2 1989 n1188 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's up, doc? (IT in health care)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cole, Louise.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Major breakthroughs in computerized medicine have benefited allpatients.andP;  Cat and DSA scanners, which cost at least three poundssterling each, together with even more sophisticated magneticresonance imaging techniques, enable accurate assessments ofbodily tissues and make surgery safer.andP;  Small, easily programmablesystems are also available for use by ordinary physicians.andP;  Theseinclude systems that use complex biochemical models to monitor andreact to patients.andP;  Many doctors continue to have reservationsabout computerization despite these benefits, however, and citesuch problems as expense, lack of formal computer training, andthe question of legal liability in case of system failure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United KingdomHealth CareComputer SystemsMISApplicationsEnd UsersMedicine.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>